<TITLE> Top Turk court backs govt reform plans, referendum </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ANKARA, July 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Turkey's top court ruled on Thursday that controversial constitutional reforms backed by the government were valid, rejecting an opposition appeal to quash them on a voting technicality. The decision, which had not been expected, paves the way for a referendum in which voters are expected to endorse the government's plans, which include allowing the Turkish people instead of parliament to elect future presidents. President Ahmet Necdet Sezer, a stern critic of the Islamist-rooted government, had also contested the reforms. "There will be a referendum," Hasim Kilic, deputy head of the Constitutional Court, told a news conference. Asked whether this meant the Turkish people would be able to elect their president directly, Kilic said: "Undoubtedly." Turkish financial markets were largely unmoved by the news. Lawmakers said the referendum, which the government is confident of winning, would take place in October. The government proposed the reforms after opposition parties, backed by the Constitutional Court, successfully blocked the election of the ruling party's presidential candidate, Foreign Minister Abdullah Gul, in parliament. That forced Prime Minister Tayyip Erdogan to call parliamentary elections on July 22, months ahead of schedule, in an attempt to break the deadlock. Turkey's secular elite, which includes top judges and army generals as well as the main opposition parties, fears Gul, an ex-Islamist, would try to boost the role of religion, a claim the government strongly denies. Most analysts had expected the Constitutional Court to uphold the opposition appeal and to rule the reforms inval
